{
  "_description": "Carbon Cap Rule (CCR) example — Benmir, Roman & Taschini (2025), 'Weitzman meets Taylor: EU allowance price drivers and carbon cap rules', Grantham Research Institute Working Paper No. 421. Two scenarios share an identical market (3 sectors, banking allowed) that is hit by a PERSISTENT emissions + abatement-cost shock from 2028 onward (an AR(1)-style hump, as in the paper). 'Fixed Cap' uses a static declining cap and lets the shock drive a sustained price spike. 'Carbon Cap Rule (CCR)' adapts each period's permit quantity to LAGGED deviations of realised emissions and abatement cost from their steady-state reference levels: Q_t = Qbar + phi_e*(e_{t-1}-ebar)/ebar + phi_z*(z_{t-1}-zbar)/zbar. With phi_z > 0 the regulator ISSUES MORE permits while abatement costs run hot (easing the sustained price elevation); with phi_e < 0 it TIGHTENS when emissions overshoot. Here the CCR cuts the carbon-price standard deviation by ~27% vs the fixed cap. Compare 'CCR Cap Adjustment', 'CCR Cost Deviation', 'CCR Emissions Deviation' and 'Equilibrium Carbon Price' across the two scenarios. NOTE: because the rule conditions on the previous period's realised outcomes (information available when the cap is set), it dampens the SUSTAINED phase of a shock rather than the impulse year itself. phi_e/phi_z are in Mt per unit fractional deviation, calibrated to THIS scenario's cap scale — they are NOT the paper's raw normalised coefficients (phi_z~0.1853, phi_e~-0.0027).",
